# Golden set for the CURATOR bake-off (packages/obscura-web/src/bench-curate.mjs), distinct from
# queries.jsonl (which scores candidate RANKING, not curation — see bench-research.mjs's own header
# for why the two need separate scorers: this one needs a live Ollama, so it cannot be a
# deterministic CI gate the way the ranking bench is).
#
# Format: {query, url, label: "relevant"|"irrelevant", note?}. `url` keys a frozen page-text
# fixture in curation-fixtures/<hash8>.txt (hash8 from url-identity.mjs, the same convention
# RESEARCH/ notes use) captured by bench-curate-capture.mjs.
#
# Every entry here is real and lived through this session's own live pipeline runs — none invented:
#
# - The three `relevant` SQLite pages and the `hard-negative` MDN pages are the EXACT case a live
#   run of this pipeline hit: querying "SQLite WAL concurrent writer locking" with the default
#   curator (phi4-mini) scored 6 MDN WritableStreamDefaultWriter pages `relevance:9` (the maximum)
#   — almost certainly fooled by literal "writer"/"lock" overlap with a completely unrelated
#   JavaScript Streams API. That live failure is why this bench exists at all.
# - `easy-negative` is a sanity floor: a curator that scores THIS as relevant is broken outright,
#   not just fooled by keyword overlap — any candidate model failing it is disqualified regardless
#   of its score on the harder cases.
# - The second query is the `vocab-mismatch` case from queries.jsonl's own philosophy: same page,
#   colloquial Spanish wording sharing almost no vocabulary with it — a curator that only pattern
#   -matches surface words should do WORSE here than on the first query's technical phrasing.

{"query": "SQLite WAL concurrent writer locking", "url": "https://www.sqlite.org/wal.html", "label": "relevant", "note": "the primary source on WAL mode itself"}
